                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      HDFC profit up 26%, stock split into five
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                                            
	Mumbai, May 3: Housing Development Finance Corporation Ltd (HDFC) today reported a 26 per cent rise in net profit for the fourth quarter ended March 2010 at Rs 926.38 crore compared with Rs 733.37 crore in the same period last year.        
	After the better-than-expected quarterly results, HDFC cheered retail investors by announcing a stock split of shares of Rs 10 each to Rs 2 apiece. The move to sub-divide the shares, following requests from several individual shareholders, is expected to boost the participation of retail investors.        
	Despite the strong growth in bottomline, HDFCs income during the fourth quarter came down to Rs 2,846.88 crore from Rs 3,145.77 crore in the same period last year. HDFC also earned Rs 45.42 crore (Rs 1.17 crore) as profit from the sale of investments.        
	For the year ended March 31, 2010, HDFCs net profit increased 24 per cent to Rs 2,826.49 crore from Rs 2,282.54 crore in the previous year.        
	As on March 2010, the loan book stood at Rs 97,967 crore against Rs 85,198 crore in the previous year  an increase of 15 per cent.         
	The spread on loans over the cost of borrowings for the year stood at 2.31 per cent against 2.21 per cent in the previous year.         
	Unrealised gains on HDFCs listed investments amounted to Rs 16,668 crore as on March 31, 2010, compared with Rs 10,236 crore.        
	Loan approvals during the year were Rs 60,611 crore against Rs 49,166 crore in the previous year, a growth of 23 per cent. Disbursements rose to Rs 50,413 crore from Rs 39,650 crore, a rise of 27 per cent. During the year, individual loan approvals and disbursements grew 53 per cent and 31 per cent, respectively.         
	Gross non-performing loans stood at Rs 782.85 crore, which are equivalent to 0.79 per cent of the portfolio.                                                                                                                                       
